• If $n = 4$, then $r_1 = 6, 7$ by (vi).

– If $r_1 = 6$, then $r_0 + r_2 + r_3 = 2r_2 + 3r_3 = 10$ by (iv). The only positive solution is $(r_0, r_2, r_3) = (6, 2, 2)$. By the proof of (vii), there is exactly one 2 in rows 2 and 3. Thus, another number 2 comes from rows 0 and 1. Now, by the proof of (vi), as row 1 cannot contain two 2's, row 1 must be $1, 3, 1, 1$.

