Recall that $a_{02}, a_{03} \ge 2$ by (xi). Also, there is only one 2 in row 0 from above. Thus, row 0 must be $1, 0, 2, 3$ or $1, 0, 3, 2$. In either case, this implies $a_{20} = a_{30} = 1$. But then $a_{21} + a_{31}$ cannot be 1 as all 6 entries 1 are used, contradicting $c_1 = 4$.

– If $r_1 = 7$, then $r_0 + r_2 + r_3 = 2r_2 + 3r_3 = 9$ by (iv). The only positive solution is $(r_0, r_2, r_3) = (5, 3, 1)$. Now, since $r_1 = 7$, by the proof of (vi), row 1 can only be $2, 1, 2, 2$, or $a_{11} = 2$, $\{a_{10}, a_{12}, a_{13}\} = \{1, 1, 3\}$. In the former case, this implies $a_{21} = 3$, contradicting (viii). In the latter case, this implies $a_{31} = 1$. As $r_3 = 1$, we have $a_{30} = a_{32} = a_{33} = 0$. This yields $a_{03} = 3$, contradicting $a_{30} = 0$.

