• If $n = 5$, then $r_1 = 8, 9$ by (vi).

– If $r_1 = 9$, then $r_0+r_2+r_3+r_4 = 2r_2+3r_3+4r_4 = 16$ by (iv). The solutions are $(r_0, r_2, r_3, r_4) = (10, 3, 2, 1), (11, 1, 2, 2)$. Also, we know that all numbers in rows 2, 3, 4 are 0 or 1 by (viii). This implies $a_{ij} = 0$ for $2 \le i, j \le 4$. It follows that $r_2 \le 2$, and so $(r_0, r_2, r_3, r_4) = (11, 1, 2, 2)$ is the only possibility.

Now, as $r_3 = r_4 = 2$, rows 3 and 4 must be $1, 1, 0, 0, 0$. This implies $a_{03} = a_{04} = 3$, but this contradicts $a_{30} = 1$.

